web: full MCP server management (list/add/toggle/remove) in browser UI

Task #4 — Manage MCP servers from the web UI.

UI (web/public/app.js):
- /mcp modal (also reachable from a new "Manage MCP servers…" row in
  the Settings modal, satisfying the task's "Settings section or its
  own panel" requirement) now renders each server as a card with:
    * status dot + canonical startup state (ready/starting/failed/cancelled/disabled),
    * configured command + args,
    * tool-name list (from the canonical { [name]: Tool } dict shape),
    * Disable/Enable and Remove buttons per row.
- Add form takes name + command-line and pushes a single canonical
  `config/value/write { keyPath: "mcp_servers.<name>", value:
  { command, args, enabled: true }, mergeStrategy: "upsert" }`.
- Toggle writes `mcp_servers.<name>.enabled = !current` with
  `upsert`. Remove writes `mcp_servers.<name> = null` with `replace`
  (the canonical "delete a sub-tree" pattern, since v2 MergeStrategy
  is only "replace" | "upsert"). Each mutation is followed by a
  `config/mcpServer/reload` and a list refresh.
- Click handling is delegated on #mcp-list so re-rendered rows stay
  wired without rebinding listeners.

Mock (web/mock-codex.mjs):
- Replaced the legacy mcpServers array with a Map<name, entry> so the
  registry can be mutated. Each list item now matches the canonical
  v2 McpServerStatus shape (tools as { [name]?: Tool }, resources,
  resourceTemplates, authStatus); UI metadata (`_enabled`,
  `_startupState`, `_command`, `_args`) rides as ignored optional
  fields.
- `mcpServer/startupStatus/updated` notifications now use the
  canonical `{ name, status, error }` payload.
- `config/value/write` actually applies `mcp_servers.*` writes:
  whole-entry add/replace, whole-entry delete (value=null + replace),
  and nested toggles for `enabled`/`command`/`args`.

Tests (web/tests/e2e.spec.mjs):
- Added a Playwright case that opens /mcp, asserts demo-fs shows
  "ready", adds a new "ephemeral" server and asserts its row
  appears, toggles demo-fs to "disabled" then back to "ready", and
  removes the ephemeral server with the confirm dialog auto-accepted.

Server gateway untouched — protocol stays strict pass-through.
